    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "that makes sense. so basically the steel acts as a skeleton or something inside the concrete to stop it from snapping if it gets pulled? can you explain more about what happens inside the material when it's under stress, like how those two forces actually interact at the microscopic level?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "You've got the right idea; the steel acts like a tensile skeleton, preventing the concrete from cracking and failing under pulling forces. At a microscopic level, when the structure is under stress, the concrete resists the squeezing forces, distributing the load. The steel, being much more ductile, bears the tensile stress, allowing the whole composite material to work together synergistically. This interaction is what gives reinforced concrete its amazing overall strength.",
      "source": "target",
